Schematic of a typical electrochemical reactor. DET direct electron transfer, MO mediated oxidation, ROS reactive oxidant species, Mn+ metal ions

When applying EO processes for wastewater treatment, the impact of some factors such as pH, electrolyte type, reactor configuration, etc. should be considered. However, among which current density (or applied voltage) and electrode (materials, shape, size, etc.) are the most significant factors influencing pollutants abatement performance of EO. Higher current density (or applied voltage) within specific range generally benefits EO process, yet serious consideration of energy cost and electrode service life should be taken into. What’s more, it is apparent that water splitting would occur and occupy the center stage of various electrochemical reactions under higher current density (or applied voltage), which, will adversely decreases EO efficiency. Preliminary quantitative analysis of energy consumption in EO processes is feasible when indexes such as the mineralization current efficiency (MCE) [128], the electrical energy required to destruct the target contaminants by one order magnitude (EEO) [129], the specific energy cost per unit mass of TOC removed (ECTOC) [130], were introduced to calculate efficiency of current or voltage used in amelioration of wastewater:7MCE%=n·F·V·Δ(TOC)4.32×107·m·I·t\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
